					<div class=3D"content"><div class=3D"heading-wrapper" data-heading-lev=
el=3D"h2"><a class=3D"anchor-link docon docon-link" href=3D"https://learn.m=
icrosoft.com/en-us/troubleshoot/microsoft-365-apps/excel/determine-a-leap-y=
ear#summary" aria-label=3D"Section titled: Summary"></a><h2 id=3D"summary" =
class=3D"heading-anchor">Summary</h2></div>
<p>This article describes how to determine whether the year in a date that =
is used in a Microsoft Excel document is a leap year.</p>
<div class=3D"heading-wrapper" data-heading-level=3D"h2"><a class=3D"anchor=
-link docon docon-link" href=3D"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troublesh=
oot/microsoft-365-apps/excel/determine-a-leap-year#more-information" aria-l=
abel=3D"Section titled: More Information"></a><h2 id=3D"more-information" c=
lass=3D"heading-anchor">More Information</h2></div>
<p>The date system that is used by Excel is based on the Gregorian calendar=
, first established in 1582 by Pope Gregory XIII. This calendar was designe=
d to correct the errors introduced by the less accurate Julian calendar.</p=
>
<p>In the Gregorian calendar, a normal year consists of 365 days. Because t=
he actual length of a sidereal year (the time required for the Earth to rev=
olve once about the Sun) is actually 365.2425 days, a "leap year" of 366 da=
ys is used once every four years to eliminate the error caused by three nor=
mal (but short) years. Any year that is evenly divisible by 4 is a leap yea=
r: for example, 1988, 1992, and 1996 are leap years.</p>
<p>However, there is still a small error that must be accounted for. To eli=
minate this error, the Gregorian calendar stipulates that a year that is ev=
enly divisible by 100 (for example, 1900) is a leap year only if it is also=
 evenly divisible by 400.</p>
<p>For this reason, the following years are not leap years:</p>
<p>1700, 1800, 1900, 2100, 2200, 2300, 2500, 2600</p>
<p>This is because they are evenly divisible by 100 but not by 400.</p>
<p>The following years are leap years: 1600, 2000, 2400</p>
<p>This is because they are evenly divisible by both 100 and 400.</p>
<p>Because versions of Microsoft Excel earlier than Excel 97 handle only ye=
ars from 1900 to 2078, only the year 1900 is subject to the 100/400 exclusi=
on rule of leap years in Microsoft Excel. However, in order to be compatibl=
e with other programs, Microsoft Excel treats the year 1900 as a leap year.=
</p>
<div class=3D"heading-wrapper" data-heading-level=3D"h3"><a class=3D"anchor=
-link docon docon-link" href=3D"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troublesh=
oot/microsoft-365-apps/excel/determine-a-leap-year#how-to-determine-whether=
-a-year-is-a-leap-year" aria-label=3D"Section titled: How to determine whet=
her a year is a leap year"></a><h3 id=3D"how-to-determine-whether-a-year-is=
-a-leap-year" class=3D"heading-anchor">How to determine whether a year is a=
 leap year</h3></div>
<p>To determine whether a year is a leap year, follow these steps:</p>
<ol>
<li>If the year is evenly divisible by 4, go to step 2. Otherwise, go to st=
ep 5.</li>
<li>If the year is evenly divisible by 100, go to step 3. Otherwise, go to =
step 4.</li>
<li>If the year is evenly divisible by 400, go to step 4. Otherwise, go to =
step 5.</li>
<li>The year is a leap year (it has 366 days).</li>
<li>The year is not a leap year (it has 365 days).</li>
</ol>
<div class=3D"heading-wrapper" data-heading-level=3D"h3"><a class=3D"anchor=
-link docon docon-link" href=3D"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/troublesh=
oot/microsoft-365-apps/excel/determine-a-leap-year#formula-to-determine-whe=
ther-a-year-is-a-leap-year" aria-label=3D"Section titled: Formula to determ=
ine whether a year is a leap year"></a><h3 id=3D"formula-to-determine-wheth=
er-a-year-is-a-leap-year" class=3D"heading-anchor">Formula to determine whe=
ther a year is a leap year</h3></div>
<p>Use the following formula to determine whether the year number that is e=
ntered into a cell (in this example, cell A1) is a leap year:</p>
<div class=3D"code-block-header margin-top-sm" data-code-block-header=3D"" =
id=3D"code-try-0" data-bi-name=3D"code-header"><!---->
		<span class=3D"code-block-header-language"><!---->excel<!----></span>
	=09
		<button type=3D"button" class=3D"button button-sm action inner-focus disp=
lay-none-print" data-bi-name=3D"copy" data-code-header-copy-button=3D"">
			<span class=3D"icon" aria-hidden=3D"true">
				<span class=3D"docon docon-edit-copy overflow-hidden"></span>
				<span data-copy-button-success-indicator=3D"" class=3D"successful-copy-=
alert position-absolute is-transparent docon docon-check-mark"></span>
			</span>
			<span><!---->Copy<!----></span>
		</button>
=09
	=09
	<!----></div><pre class=3D"inner-focus" role=3D"group" aria-label=3D"Horiz=
ontally scrollable code" tabindex=3D"0" data-language=3D"excel"><code class=
=3D"lang-excel"><span>=3D<span class=3D"hljs-built_in">IF</span>(<span clas=
s=3D"hljs-built_in">OR</span>(<span class=3D"hljs-built_in">MOD</span>(<spa=
n class=3D"hljs-symbol">A1</span>,<span class=3D"hljs-number">400</span>)=
=3D<span class=3D"hljs-number">0</span>,<span class=3D"hljs-built_in">AND</=
span>(<span class=3D"hljs-built_in">MOD</span>(<span class=3D"hljs-symbol">=
A1</span>,<span class=3D"hljs-number">4</span>)=3D<span class=3D"hljs-numbe=
r">0</span>,<span class=3D"hljs-built_in">MOD</span>(<span class=3D"hljs-sy=
mbol">A1</span>,<span class=3D"hljs-number">100</span>)&lt;&gt;<span class=
=3D"hljs-number">0</span>)),<span class=3D"hljs-string">"Leap Year"</span>,=
 <span class=3D"hljs-string">"NOT a Leap Year"</span>) =20
</span></code></pre>
<div class=3D"buttons buttons-right margin-bottom-none margin-top-sm"><!---=
